Looking at this proof goal, I need to prove that `a.abs = b ↔ a = b ∨ a = -b` given that `0 ≤ b`.

The absolute value is defined as `Rat.abs x = if x < 0 then -x else x`.

For the forward direction: if `a.abs = b`, then either `a < 0` (so `-a = b`, i.e., `a = -b`) or `a ≥ 0` (so `a = b`).

For the backward direction: if `a = b`, then since `0 ≤ b`, we have `a ≥ 0`, so `a.abs = a = b`. If `a = -b`, then `a ≤ 0`, so `a.abs = -a = -(-b) = b`.

```lean
theorem abs_eq {a b : Rat} (hb : 0 ≤ b) : a.abs = b ↔ a = b ∨ a = -b := by
  constructor
  · intro h
    unfold Rat.abs at h
    split at h
    · right; omega
    · left; omega
  · intro h
    unfold Rat.abs
    cases h with
    | inl h => 
      subst h
      split
      · next h => simp at h; exact Rat.nonneg_antisymm hb (Rat.nonneg_iff_sub_nonpos.mpr h)
      · rfl
    | inr h =>
      subst h
      split
      · next h => simp
      · next h => simp at h; exact Rat.nonneg_antisymm (Rat.nonneg_sub_iff_nonpos.mpr h) hb
```
